{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503446"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:00:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2029"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2029"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.4,0.07,0.36,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2029"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83301"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34665"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of abdominal pain. The pain began around her umbilicus and has migrated to the right lower abdomen. She has nausea and has had a single non-bilious vomit. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was four weeks ago and she uses barrier contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the right iliac fossa with guarding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the LEAST likely cause of her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appendicitis","Mesenteric adenitis","Ectopic pregnancy","Pyelonephritis","Ovarian torsion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggesting peritoneal irritation in the right iliac fossa. The differential diagnosis must consider the anatomical structures in this region, particularly in a woman of reproductive age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric adenitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the least likely diagnosis as it predominantly affects children under 10 years of age and is rare in adults. It typically occurs following an upper respiratory tract infection, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a likely diagnosis given the classic migration of pain from periumbilical to right iliac fossa, associated with fever and localised peritonism. This remains the most common surgical cause of right iliac fossa pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E must be considered in any woman of reproductive age with abdominal pain, regardless of contraceptive use. The timing of her last menstrual period and the presence of barrier contraception does not exclude this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with loin pain and systemic symptoms, but can cause right-sided abdominal pain if there is significant renal inflammation or perinephric involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian torsion\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset severe unilateral pain but can have a more gradual onset. It is a surgical emergency that can affect women of any age and requires prompt diagnosis to preserve ovarian function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mesenteric adenitis is predominantly a disease of children, rarely occurring in adults.","Right iliac fossa pain in women of reproductive age requires consideration of gynaecological causes including ectopic pregnancy and ovarian torsion.","The classic migration of periumbilical pain to the right iliac fossa suggests appendicitis but requires careful exclusion of other diagnoses."],"references":["Cartwright SL, Knudson MP. Evaluation of acute abdominal pain in adults. Am Fam Physician. 2008;77(7):971-978. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2008/0401/p971.html","Helbling R, Conficconi E, Wyttenbach M, et al. Acute Nonspecific Mesenteric Lymphadenitis: More Than \u0022No Need for Surgery\u0022. Biomed Res Int. 2017;2017:9784565. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28261620/","Huang C, Hong MK, Ding DC. A review of ovary torsion. Ci Ji Yi Xue Za Zhi. 2017;29(3):143-147. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28974907/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83301"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2029"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83301"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T21:25:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T21:26:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2029"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"